column1: Before 1 September 2020, will Cameroon's Paul Biya and/or Togo's Faure Gnassingbé cease to be the president of their respective countries?
column5: ['Yes, only President Paul Biya', 'Yes, only President Faure Gnassingbé', 'Yes, both', 'No']
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit']

Given the short time to the timeline of this challenge , I am proposing both to be inlace 1 September. I would give Gnassingbe (Togo) given his relative youth, progressive economic (if corrupt) policies somewhat longer. Biya (Cameroon) is 87 with an repressive administration, increasing poverty and terrorism and therefore a limited time as president. Covid-19 will have a distraction for insurrection, although Biya would be susceptible to succumbing to the disease.
All in now.
Leaving 1% chance given Biya's age, otherwise seeing either leaders ceasing to be pres is unlikely.

Some Special Forces groups going to anglophone areas are dissatisfied with having to go there as opposed to the group that protects Biya. I will go with crowd on this but keep an eye on his military.
Extremely unlikely. Covid-19 has dictators strengthening their grip. At the same time, should they succumb to Covid-19, there will be change.

Given Biya’s age and how he was missing in April it is hard to give no the 98% consensus. Since it is a short time to the end of this question and I can find no negative information on Biya’s health I will go a long way in that direction.

Death from COVID of Biya seems the most likely possibility for him to be removed from office [1]. There is little news on Gnassingbé newer than Feb, so he is likely in a stable position. 1% for COVID against Biya.
Don't know enough about this

President Biya is the most vulnerable of the two men. While Cameroon has one of the best economies on the African continent, falling oil prices, a world wide recession resulting in reduced demand for Cameroon's natural resources, and the COVID19 pandemic have negatively impacted the country's economic status. Discontent and conflict between the English and French speaking regions weighs heavily on the President as well. President Biya's age and questionable health prior to even factoring in his risk level with COVID19 increase the possibility that he will no longer be able to serve as President for an extended period. President Gnassingbe benefits from wide support despite the extremely poor economic conditions in Togo. Supporters most likely believe he provides political stability at a time when the country has been attempting to improve infrastructure and increase employment opportunities.
Both seem safe, not loved, but autocratically safe.

Ok...Biya in power 37 years is 87 years old and we are in a coronavirus pandemic. I better raise his being out. Faure? https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/articles/28582/it-will-take-more-than-an-election-to-oust-faure-gnassingbe-in-togo

No news is good news for these leaders staying in power. I'll forecast no change by Sept.

Much speculation has surrounded Biya’s health lately especially now during the pandemic, not to mention that at 87 he’s Africa’s oldest head of state and government. His absence from public life is exacerbated by the previous four decade rule where he was mostly front and center. In Cameroon’s English speaking north, a practical break away state exists in the form of Ambazonia. Since March this conflict has been on hold due to the pandemic, but an insurgency is always anyways an inherent risk in a multi-decade autocratic rule. At his age he’s much more likely to simply die in office at this point.

Rumors continue to run rampant regarding Biya, with continued political pressure to step down or otherwise remove him [1]. There is video of him from April 8th with the French ambassador, so he appears to be alive [1].
https://www.journalducameroun.com/en/cameroon-president-biya-cancels-labour-day-national-unity-day-celebrations-due-to-covid-19/ Biya probably not losing job during crisis. Keep checking.
Just by virtue of age, there is a chance of Paul Biya dying in the next six months, [1]. He's a prime target for C-19, and he is notably absent, [4], but does appear to still be alive, [5]

Paul Biya is an 87 year old male. In the UK, 1 in 6 males die before their 88th birthday. He has access to high level healthcare as a head of state/ wealthy individual, which bumps this down a bit (lets say 1/10).
Shaving my forecast based on no real data.
Togo election has come and gone with no real challenge to Gnassingbe, so I'm trimming B accordingly.

Updating for passage of time based on my previous calculations. For Biya likelihood of death between now and September is now 6/12 x 10.8% = roughly 5%. An extra month has passed since my last estimate so reducing estimate he is removed from power by 1% to 4%. Total 9% chance he's removed from office.
Trimming B further as Togo's election wraps up with African Union endorsement and no signs of serious social unrest. Will cut again soon if that holds.

Trimming A by one for passage of time, and trimming B by 2 on Gnassingbe's election win. That win was expected, but some of the probability I had here was to cover the unlikely event that he lost. The opposition is protesting the results, but that is almost pro forma in elections like these nowadays, so I don't see it as an informative event.

Nudging up slightly on my forecast for Biya exiting office as legislative elections wind down in Cameroon with all of the expected noise: landslide win for ruling party, opposition boycott and allegations of fraud, some violence in separatist regions (see link below). Results are supposed to be announced on March 1, so if we're going to see much (new) drama in Cameroon before this question closes, there's a good chance it will happen then.

Affirming prior forecast, but taking this opportunity to share One Earth Future Foundation's inaugural Election-Related Violence Intelligence System (ELVIS) report, which covers both Cameroon and Togo.

When it comes to Paul Biya He will most likely stay president of Cameroon given the fact that the election this year is only for the parliament. The only way that I can see him not remain in office is if he dies which is a probable scenario given that he is 86 years old and continues to have health issues When it comes to Gnassingbé He will also most likely stay in power as well because the government has already killed protesters who wanted a term limit so the protesters do not have the force to combat them. Also given the fact his family has been in power since the 1960s and that his family has de facto control of both the constitutional court and the Independent National Electoral Commission it is unlikely given the current circumstances that he will be ousted as president anytime soon. https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2019/togo https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2019/cameroon https://www.cameroonintelligencereport.com/biyas-health-panic-in-yaounde/

They were delayed before and the Anglophone area is trying to break away and presenting somewhat if an armed conflict. Biya is backed by France who has a lot of business there. The young, 25% of population, are under 25 and do nit like him. https://actucameroun.com/2020/02/03/chimamanda-ngozi-adichie-paul-biya-est-au-pouvoir-depuis-ma-naissance-cest-ridicule/ It is said since 1992 he has won by corrupt means. Upshot is country is unstable and he may be forced to step down. Faure Gnassingbé Is running for 4th five year term. He won by 59% of vote in 2015 and protests after thru 2019 were crushed. Do not see him losing grip on power.

Revising thanks to @ulfelder helping me read what I should have read before (esp. re. no presidential election in Cameroon).

Cameroon: no presidential election this year, only legislative, so the chief risk is that Biya, who is old and has been rumored to be quite ill at various times, dies in office. Even if he is not in great health, though, that's unlikely to happen in the next 8 months. Throw in a percentage point or two for black swan political events, and I get to something like a 4-percent chance Biya exits office before September.
Yeah, I know--these are pretty weaselly numbers, so I suppose I'll have to do some more research. This will cut into my nap time. (My longstanding mantra: "There's a nap for that.")

From the Economist "In ..Togo two generations of the Gnassingbé family have ,,, held the top job since 1967." "Cameroon, which has been under the thumb of Paul Biya for 37 years, is falling apart while its octogenarian president spends much of his time at ... a Hotel in Geneva." With no specific insights my forecast will be bland.
